title: For Sale:  French MAS 36 7.5mm Military Rifle, Unissued, Two Boxes of Shells
postcontent:
.	Never shot, unissued, always a cabinet queen
.	Beautiful hardwood stock, no dings or scratches
.	Beautiful shiny bore with very distinct rifling
.	French MAS Model 36 bolt action military rifle in 7.5mm MLE
.	Two boxes of shells included on 20 Rnd (Modern) and one 15 Rnd (probably a 
        collectors item itself)
.	Mauser type action, 
.	Spike bayonet (Geneva Convention legal?)
.	All original matching numbers on receiver, bolt, etc.
.	Original leather sling (shown)
.	French Resistance and troops used this in WWII
.	Used by French military as late as Vietnam

Here's a recent and similar example that sold on GunsAmerica:

http://www.gunsamerica.com/910574414/Guns/Rifles/Military-Misc-Rifles-Non-US/FrenchMAS/MAS_36.htm

.	Transaction to be Face-to-Face (FTF), cash only.

.	Pictures are of the actual rifle and other include items

.	If interested, please email: REDACTED or call REDACTED

More History/Info
-------------------
 Caliber: 7.5x54 mm
Overall length: 1020 mm
Barrel length: 575 mm
Weight: 3.7 kg empty
Magazine capacity: 5 rounds

French army was among the first to adopt the smokeless rifle ammunition in the form of 8mm Lebel cartridge in 1886. By the early 1920s this rimmed cartridge became obsolete, so French began to develop a more modern, rimless cartridge, more suitable for proposed lightweight machine guns. By the 1924 French army had the new 7.5mm cartridge, but this proved to be unsuccessful, and by the 1929 the updated version of the 7.5mm ammunition has been adopted as 7.5mm Cartouche Mle.1929C (7.5x54mm). By the same time, French also developed a lightweight machinegun, the MAC 1929. Initially, French tried to convert earlier 8mm Berthier rifles for new ammunition, but it was apparent that the new rifle is desirable for French infantry. In 1936 French military officially adopted the MAS Mle.1936 (MAS-36) bolt-action rifle, developed by the Manufacture D'Armes de Saint-Etienne. Later on, French forces adopted the modified paratrooper's version, known as MAS-36 CR 39. This version differed from basic rifle by the aluminum buttstock, which can be folded down and under the forend. This rifle served with French armed forces until the semi-automatic MAS-49 and MAS-49/56 replaced it in service during 1950s and 1960s. The MAS-36 rifle was in production up until the mid-1950s. The MAS-36 action also served as a platform for FR F-1 and FR F-2 sniper rifles, which are still in service with French Armed forces. Since 1951, some of MAS-36 rifles were converted or made into MAS-36/51 pattern, by adding the permanently attached grenade launchers and rifle grenade sights. Grenade launcher was attached to the muzzle of the gun, and was used to launch rifle grenades using special blank ammunition. Folding grenade sight was attached to the left side of the front sight base.

MAS-36 is a manually operated, magazine fed, rotating bolt action rifle. The rotating bolt has two opposing lugs, located at the rear of the bolt body. The bolt locks into receiver walls, the bolt handle is located at the rear of the bolt, and is bent forward for more comfortable operation. The square-shaped receiver is machined from steel, and contained integral magazine. Magazine is loaded using charging clips or single rounds, with clip guides machined into the receiver bridge. The wooden stock is made from two parts (buttstock and forend), both connected to the uncovered receiver. The spike-shaped bayonet is stored in the tube below the barrel in reversed position, when not in use. Diopter rear sight is located at the rear of the receiver, and marked from 100 to 1 200 meters in 100 meters increments. Probably the most noticeable feature of the MAS-36 is the lack of any manual safety - rifle was supposed to be carried with empty magazine, and loaded only before the actual combat.

--

title: For Sale:  Just a friendly reminder
postcontent:
This is a great, community-driven site. I've used Armslist for sales and purchases many times, and visit it with great regularity. 
I am just making a friendly point to anyone posting: This is a site for private sales and transactions, sort of the craigslist of guns. If you are a seller, and you have an FFL, that is great, and you're serving the gun community well. But you shouldn't post a sale here, and demand that the buyer have the weapon transfered to him through an FFL, and fill out the 4473 and take a criminal background check. 

There are plenty of places for gunshops to advertise. This is not one of them. This is a place where law-abiding citizens can excercise their rights to LEGALLY buy, sell, and trade their firearms without fear of the Fed getting involved and making into an ordeal it was never meant to be. 
Private sales are king here. Paperwork is not.

Excercise your rights, or they'll be lost forever. 
Thank you for taking the time to read this.

title: For Sale:  First Pistol S&W made
postcontent:
Incredible Pistol model of 1913.  Smith and Wesson's first venture into the semi-auto pistol field consisted of a design based  on the Belgian-made Clement pistols.  Initial production was for a S&W proprietary cartridge the .35 S&W auto.
.35 S&W auto has a 7-shot magazine, 3 and 1/2 inch barrel blue finish with walnut grips.
This neat little pistol has 2 safeties a round roll disc where the web of  the hand fits and a push button middle finger operated under the trigger guard.  These are uncommon pistols which were not a success for S&W the next try at a semi-auto pistol would be 20 years later which was the first generation 9mm DAs
  This pistol is a type 3 marked 35 auto CTG which was produced about 1913 with the two safeties mentioned but no magazine safety.  The pistol is excellent plus with 2 perfect walnut grips with the S&W trademark on each side, mechanically excellent and finish blueing better than 90%.  If you have never seen one of these they are well worth looking up on google or the Neal and Jinks Historical Book of S&W.
  Again for those collectors trying to accumulate all 8 variations of the .35 Semi-Automatic Pistol (model of 1913)  this is a type 3.

title: For Sale:  Rossi M88 "Lady Rossi" .38 SPL
postcontent:
I have up for sale, or trade, a nice Rossi M88 "Lady Rossi", CAL .38.

It is in exceptional condition, and has had very few rounds put through it. Everything is still TIGHT on this beautiful 5 shot revolver! It has a polished finish, and wood grips, and it comes with the original box, manuals, and velvet bag.

I bought this for my wife to use as her primary carry weapon. She used it for qualifying for her AZ Concealed carry permit, and fired maybe a total of 20 rounds through it on that day. Since then it has been sitting in a padded case in my safe, because she decided she wanted to carry a compact .45 instead. I see no reason to keep this sitting in the safe taking up space where I could put a new 1911, so I am putting it up for sale or trade.

I am looking to get $200 cash. I would consider possible trades for electronics such as Widescreen LCD or Plasma televisions 21" or larger (preferably larger), or Widescreen LCD computer monitors 24" or larger. I would also consider trades for an 8gb or larger Ipod or Zune, go-carts, golf carts, or computers (laptops and desktop/towers) of equal or greater value. Other interesting trades MIGHT be considered, just tell me what you have, and I'll let you know if I'm interested. Items must be in working, usable condition. No Junk please. 

You can see pictures at http://www.sonicperfection.com/LadyRossi/

Thank You.
